1. Launch Two EC2 Instances
Instance 1: For WordPress application.
Instance 2: For MySQL database.
Instance Details:
Use the t2.micro instance type with an Ubuntu AMI.
Configure security groups as follows:
WordPress Instance: Allow HTTP (port 80) and SSH (port 22).
MySQL Instance: Allow MySQL (port 3306) with access restricted to the WordPress instance IP, and SSH (port 22).

2. Set Up MySQL Instance
SSH into the MySQL instance.
Install MySQL:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install mysql-server -y
Configure MySQL:
Create a WordPress database and user with remote access permissions.
sudo mysql
CREATE DATABASE wordpress;
CREATE USER 'wp_user'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'password';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON wordpress.* TO 'wp_user'@'%';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;
Edit MySQL configuration file to allow external connections:
sudo nano /etc/mysql/mysql.conf.d/mysqld.cnf
Comment out bind-address to allow remote connections and restart MySQL:
sudo systemctl restart mysql

3. Set Up WordPress Instance
SSH into the WordPress instance.
Install Apache, PHP, and other dependencies:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install apache2 php libapache2-mod-php php-mysql -y
Download and Configure WordPress:
wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz
tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz
sudo mv wordpress /var/www/html/
Configure WordPress to Use Remote MySQL:
Edit the wp-config.php file in the WordPress directory:
sudo nano /var/www/html/wordpress/wp-config.php
Update the database details to point to the MySQL instance:
define('DB_NAME', 'wordpress');
define('DB_USER', 'wp_user');
define('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');
define('DB_HOST', 'MYSQL_INSTANCE_IP'); // Replace with the MySQL instance's IP

4. Access WordPress and Complete Setup
Open the public IP of the WordPress instance in a browser.
Complete the WordPress installation steps to set up the site.
Create a Welcome Page in WordPress and set it as the homepage.
